Definition 2.3. Let $F:\mathcal{A}\to\mathcal{B}$ be an additive functor between two mixed abelian categories. The weight amplitude of $F$ is defined to be the infimum of the set $\left\{a\in\mathbb{Z}_{\geq 0}\mid\text{$F(\mathcal{A}_{\leq n})\subset% \mathcal{B}_{\leq n+a}$ for all $n\in\mathbb{Z}$}\right\}\cup\{+\infty\}.$
Definition 1.1. A $k$-linear functor $F:{\sf Qcoh}X\rightarrow{\sf Qcoh}Y$ is totally global if for every open immersion $u:U\rightarrow X$ with $U$ affine, $Fu_{*}=0$.
4.1.1 Definition A poset $J$ is said to be left-filtered (or, equivalently for posets, left-directed) if for any pair of elements $x,y\in J$ there is an element $z$ with $z\leq x,y$. One similarly defines right-filtered/right-directed posets by reversing the inequalities. $\blacklozenge$
2.3.24 Definition Let $A$ be a 2-ring. A left $A$-2-module is an $A$-module object in 2AbGp; i.e. it is a 2-abelian group $M$, a map $A\boxtimes M\to M$, and an associator intertwining the two maps $A\boxtimes A\boxtimes M\to M$, satisfying some compatibility conditions. When $A$ is a commutative 2-ring, we denote by $A\textsc{-2Mod}$ its 2-category of 2-modules. It has a symmetric monoidal structure $\boxtimes_{A}$, similar to the analogous structure on the module category of a commutative 1-algebra. A (commutative) $A$-2-algebra is a (commutative) monoid object in $A\textsc{-2Mod}$; we write $A\textsc{-Com2Alg}$ for the category of commutative $A$-2-algebras. A commutative $A$-2-algebra structure on a commutative 2-ring $B$ is the same as a commutative 2-ring morphism $A\to B$. Consequently, the 2-category $A\textsc{-Com2Alg}$ can also be described as follows: the objects are the commutative 2-ring morphisms $A\to B$; the morphisms between $A\overset{f}{\rightarrow}B$ and $A\overset{g}{\rightarrow}C$ are the pairs $(h,\zeta)$, where $h:B\to C$ is a 1-morphism of in Com2Ring and $\zeta:g\Rightarrow h\circ f$ is a 2-isomorphism in Com2Ring; a 2-morphism $(h,\zeta)\Rightarrow(h^{\prime},\zeta^{\prime})$ is a 2-morphism $\xi:h\Rightarrow h^{\prime}$ such that $\zeta^{\prime}=(\xi.f)\zeta$, where we denote “whiskering of a 2-morphism by a 1-morphism” by a lower dot, and the “2-composition” by concatenation. $\blacklozenge$
6.2.5 Definition The walking idempotent is the category $M$ with one object $\bullet$ and a non-identity morphism $m:\bullet\to\bullet$ satisfying $m^{2}=m$. The walking projection is its idempotent splitting: it is the category $P$ with two objects $\bullet,\circ$, generated by the morphisms $p:\bullet\to\circ$ and $i:\circ\to\bullet$, with the relation $\operatorname{id}_{\circ}=\{\circ\overset{i}{\to}\bullet\overset{p}{\to}\circ\}$. $\blacklozenge$
3.2.10 Definition A functor is conservative if it reflects isomorphisms. $\blacklozenge$
4.2.19 Definition A cartesian 2-ring is said to be good if its coproducts are disjoint and stable. A commutative 2-ring $A$ is good if $\textsc{Cog}(A)$ is a good cartesian 2-ring (see proposition 3.3.22). We denote by Good2Rings the 2-category of good commutative 2-rings with the usual 1- and 2-morphisms, and by Good2AfSch its 1-opposite. GoodCart will be the category of good cartesian 2-rings. $\blacklozenge$
2.1.1 Definition Fix a cardinal $\kappa$; a set is $\kappa$-small if its cardinality is strictly less than $\kappa$, and a category is $\kappa$-small if its collection of arrows is. A $\kappa$-directed category is a poset in which every $\kappa$-small set of objects has an upper bound. A $\kappa$-directed colimit is the colimit of a diagram for which the indexing category is $\kappa$-directed. An object $x$ of a category is $\kappa$-little if $\operatorname{Hom}(x,-)$ preserves $\kappa$-directed colimits. An object is little if it is $\kappa$-little for some $\kappa$. A category $C$ is presentable if it is locally small and cocomplete and there exists a set $S$ of objects, all of which are little, such that the cocompletion in $C$ of (the full subcategory on) $S$ is the entire category $C$. A category is $\kappa$-presentable if the generating set can be taken to consist entirely of $\kappa$-little objects. $\blacklozenge$
1.1.4 Definition Let $G$ be a small category, and $R$ a commutative ring, and denote by ${}^{G}\textsc{Mod}^{R}$ (resp. $\textsc{Mod}^{R}$) the category of $G$-representations on $R$-modules (resp. the category of $R$-modules). Then $\textsc{Mod}^{R}$ is symmetric monoidal on account of $R$ being commutative, and ${}^{G}\textsc{Mod}^{R}$ inherits a symmetric monoidal structure of “pointwise tensor product.” The Tannaka-Krein category $\operatorname{TK}(G,R)$ has as its objects the symmetric monoidal cocontinuous $R$-linear functors ${{}^{G}\textsc{Mod}^{R}}\to{\textsc{Mod}^{R}}$, and as its morphisms the monoidal natural transformations. $\blacklozenge$
4.1.4 Definition If $C$ is a (2,1)-category, a functor $F:C\to\textsc{Gpd}$ is pro-representable if it is (equivalent to a functor) of the form $\operatorname{Hom}_{\textsc{Pro-}C}(x,-):C\to\textsc{Gpd}$ for some pro-object $x\in\textsc{Pro-}C$. $\blacklozenge$
3.1.1 Definition Let $A$ be a commutative 2-ring. The fundamental or Galois pro-groupoid of $A$ is the 2-functor $\textsc{Gpd}\to\textsc{CAT}$ from small groupoids to possibly large but locally small categories defined, for any small groupoid $G$, by: $\pi_{1}(A)(G)=\operatorname{Hom}_{A\textsc{-ComAlg}}(^{G}A,A).$ The fundamental pro-finite groupoid of $A$ is the 2-functor $\pi_{1}^{f}(A):\textsc{Gpd}_{f}\to\textsc{CAT}$ from finite groupoids to categories defined by the same formula. $\blacklozenge$
4.1.5 Definition A (2,1)-category is finitely complete if it admits finite products and equalizers. A functor between (2,1)-categories is finitely continuous if it preserves finite products and equalizers. $\blacklozenge$
2.3.22 Definition A 2-ring is an algebra object in 2AbGp. Equivalently, a 2-ring is a presentable monoidal category for which the monoidal structure distributes over colimits. 2-rings are the objects of a 2-category 2Ring: 1-morphisms in 2Ring are 1-morphisms of the underlying 2-abelian groups equipped with the structure of monoidal functors, and 2-morphisms in 2Ring are monoidal natural transformations between 1-morphisms. A commutative 2-ring is a 2-ring equipped with a symmetric structure. Commutative 2-rings form a 2-category Com2Ring whose 1-morphisms are those 1-morphisms of the underlying 2-rings that intertwine the symmetric structures. The 2-morphisms are left unchanged, so that for any two commutative 2-rings $A,B$, the category $\operatorname{Hom}_{\textsc{Com2Ring}}(A,B)$ is a full subcategory of $\operatorname{Hom}_{\textsc{2Ring}}(A,B)$. The category 2AfSch of affine 2-schemes is 1-opposite to the category of commutative 2-rings. Given a commutative 2-ring $A$, we write $\operatorname{2Spec}(A)$ for the corresponding affine 2-scheme. $\blacklozenge$
3.3.19 Definition A 2-ring $A$ is cartesian if its monoidal structure is the one given by the binary product and terminal object. $\blacklozenge$
2.1.8 Definition The 2-category 2AbGp of 2-abelian groups has as objects the presentable categories. A 1-morphism of 2-abelian groups $f:A\to B$ is the data consisting of a left adjoint $f^{*}:A\to B$ and its right adjoint $f_{*}:B\to A$. Given $f,g:A\to B$ two 1-morphisms, a 2-morphism in the category of 2-abelian groups is a natural transformation $\eta:f^{*}\to g^{*}$; this uniquely determines an adjoint natural transformation $\eta^{\dagger}:g_{*}\to f_{*}$. $\blacklozenge$
3.2.4 Definition Let $G$ be a groupoid and $A$ a commutative 2-ring. Let $\hat{y}\in A^{G}$ be a cocommutative coalgebra, and $y=U(\hat{y})\in A^{G_{0}}$ its associated sorted object. Using the notations introduced before lemma 2.4.37, $\hat{y}$ is said to be a right $G$-pseudotorsor in $A$ if $\tau_{y}$ is an isomorphism. If in addition the counit $\hat{y}\to 1_{A}$ is a colimiting cocone, we call $\hat{y}$ a right G-torsor. The category of $G$-torsors in $A$ with maps of coalgebras in $A^{G}$ as morphisms is denoted by $\textsc{Tors}(G,A)$. $\blacklozenge$
4.2.18 Definition Let $A$ be a cartesian 2-ring. We say that $A$ has disjoint coproducts if whenever we have an expression $\displaystyle a=\coprod_{i\in I}a_{i}$ in $A$ of an object $a$ as a coproduct, the canonical maps $a_{i}\to a$ are monomorphisms, and the pullbacks $a_{i}\times_{a}a_{j}$ are the initial object for all $i\neq j\in I$. We say that coproducts in $A$ are stable if for any map $\displaystyle b\to a=\coprod_{i\in I}a_{i}$ in $A$, the canonical maps $b_{i}=b\times_{a}a_{i}\to b$ make $b$ the coproduct $\displaystyle\coprod_{i\in I}b_{i}$. $\blacklozenge$
2.4.36 Definition Let $A$ be a 2-abelian group and $G$ a small category. The category ${}^{G}A$ consists of the left $G$-representations in $A$, and $A^{G}$ are the right $G$-representations in $A$. The regular representation of a category $G$ is the object ${{}^{G}G^{G}}\in{{}^{G}\textsc{Set}^{G}}$ corresponding to $\operatorname{Hom}_{G}:G^{\rm op}\times G\to\textsc{Set}$. Let $G_{0}$ denote the category with no nontrivial morphisms on the set of objects in $G$; the inclusion $G_{0}\hookrightarrow G$ induces forgetful functors $U:{{}^{G}\textsc{Set}}\to{{}^{G_{0}}\textsc{Set}}$ and $\textsc{Set}^{G}\to\textsc{Set}^{G_{0}}$. Since $G_{0}$ has no nontrivial morphisms, there is a canonical identification ${}^{G_{0}}A=A^{G_{0}}$ for any 2-abelian group $A$, and we call its objects $G_{0}$-sorted objects in $A$. The left (resp. right) regular representation of $G$ is the object ${}^{G}G$ ($G^{G}$) in ${}^{G}\textsc{Set}^{G_{0}}$ (${}^{G_{0}}\textsc{Set}^{G}$) formed from ${}^{G}G^{G}$ by forgetting the right (left) action. $\blacklozenge$
